Park Elevate is a space-efficient automated parking solution built around a vertical carousel (Giant Wheel) mechanism that accommodates four vehicles—designated as Slots A, B, C, and D—within a fraction of the ground footprint demanded by conventional surface parking. A High-Torque DC Gear Motor, managed by an L298N dual H-bridge motor driver, rotates the carousel structure through precise 90-degree indexing steps, bringing any designated slot to the ground-level entry or exit position on demand. An ESP32 microcontroller acts as the central embedded controller: it hosts a localised Wi-Fi hotspot through which users exclusively access the system's web application, ensuring that no unintended device or internet traffic can interfere with parking operations.
The software layer is composed of a Python–Flask backend and an HTML5/CSS frontend communicating via the Fetch API. User credentials and slot-assignment records are maintained in a lightweight flat-file JSON database (parking_data.json). The session flow enforces authentication before any mechanical movement is triggered, displays a Parking Full notification when all slots are occupied, and calculates parking charges at Rs. 2 per five minutes upon vehicle retrieval. The project was conceived and executed through the Stanford five-stage Design Thinking process—Empathise, Define, Ideate, Prototype, and Test—ensuring that every technical decision is anchored in a verified user need. This report documents the complete Design Thinking journey, including the hardware architecture, software design, prototype evaluation, and iterative redesign of Park Elevate.
